gages with the possibility of democracy and the ethical, and allows us to begin to conceive of what it might mean to be human.This exciting approach to literary theory will be of interest to lecturers and students of literary theory and criticism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aIgnorance (Theory of knowledge) in literature. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Essays.2bisacsh  aRomantic period.  aagnoiology.  ademocracy.  aethical.  aignorance.  aliterary texts.  aliterature.  anarrative force.  anot knowing.  apoetics.1 aBennett, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779269340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847792693423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847792693/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles